                            "Explain Erik Erikson's eight stages of psychosocial development, highlighting their importance in human growth.",
                          answer:
                            "Erik Erikson’s theory of psychosocial development outlines eight key stages that individuals pass through from infancy to old age, each characterized by a central conflict that shapes their personality and social functioning. His work emphasizes the **social nature of human growth** and how relationships and societal factors influence development.\n\n1. **Trust vs. Mistrust (Birth to 18 months)**: Infants depend on caregivers for basic needs. When these needs are consistently met, they develop trust. Failure to do so results in mistrust.\n\n2. **Autonomy vs. Shame and Doubt (2–3 years)**: Children begin to assert independence. Success leads to autonomy; overly harsh criticism can result in shame and self-doubt.\n\n3. **Initiative vs. Guilt (3–5 years)**: Children start to take initiative in play and social interactions. Successful resolution fosters a sense of purpose, while too much restriction can result in guilt.\n\n4. **Industry vs. Inferiority (6–11 years)**: Children develop a sense of pride in their abilities and accomplishments. Encouragement leads to a sense of industry, while repeated failure can create feelings of inferiority.\n\n5. **Identity vs. Role Confusion (12–18 years)**: Adolescents explore personal identity and future roles. Successful resolution results in a strong sense of self; failure leads to confusion about one’s place in the world.\n\n6. **Intimacy vs. Isolation (19–40 years)**: Young adults seek deep, meaningful relationships. Success leads to the virtue of love, while failure can result in isolation and loneliness.\n\n7. **Generativity vs. Stagnation (40–65 years)**: Adults strive to contribute to society through work or family. Success leads to a sense of generativity and care, while stagnation can result in self-absorption.\n\n8. **Integrity vs. Despair (65+ years)**: In old age, people reflect on their lives. Those who feel fulfilled experience wisdom and integrity; those with regrets may face despair.\n\nErikson’s theory is important because it highlights how **each life stage builds upon the previous**. Successfully resolving these conflicts results in positive virtues like hope, will, purpose, competence, fidelity, love, care, and wisdom. Thus, his model offers a holistic view of how social experiences shape identity and well-being throughout life.",
                          codeBlock: "",
                          language: "",
