                            "Explain the working principle of stacks in data structures and how they are implemented using arrays in C. Include code examples and discuss the potential issues of overflow and underflow.",
                          answer:
                            'A stack is a linear data structure that follows the Last In, First Out (LIFO) principle, where the last element inserted is the first one to be removed. This structure is analogous to a stack of plates where the plate placed last on top is the first to be removed. In computer memory, a stack can be implemented using arrays or linked lists.\n\nIn an array-based stack implementation in C, an array is used to store the stack elements and a variable `top` is used to track the index of the top element. Initially, the stack is empty, and `top` is set to -1. To push an element, `top` is incremented, and the element is placed at the `top` index. To pop an element, the element at `top` is removed, and `top` is decremented.\n\nHowever, this implementation has limitations, specifically stack overflow and underflow. **Stack overflow** occurs when trying to push an element into a full stack, and **stack underflow** occurs when trying to pop an element from an empty stack.\n\nHere’s a sample code snippet illustrating stack operations:\n\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n#define SIZE 5\nint stack[SIZE], top = -1;\n\nvoid push(int value) {\n    if(top == SIZE - 1) {\n        printf("Stack Overflow\\n");\n    } else {\n        stack[++top] = value;\n    }\n}\n\nint pop() {\n    if(top == -1) {\n        printf("Stack Underflow\\n");\n        return -1;\n    } else {\n        return stack[top--];\n    }\n}\n\nint main() {\n    push(10);\n    push(20);\n    printf("Popped element: %d\\n", pop());\n    return 0;\n}\n```\n\nThis code pushes two elements onto the stack and pops one, handling both overflow and underflow conditions appropriately. By carefully managing the `top` variable and checking conditions, stack operations can be implemented safely and efficiently in C.',
