                            'A **queue** is a linear data structure that follows the **First In, First Out (FIFO)** principle, where the first element added to the queue is the first one to be removed. This makes it analogous to a line of people waiting for a service, where the person at the front leaves first, and new arrivals join at the rear.\n\nQueues are implemented using arrays or linked lists. In an **array-based implementation** in C, two pointers (or indices), `front` and `rear`, are used to keep track of the queue\'s front and rear. Initially, both are set to -1 to indicate an empty queue.\n\n### Basic Operations:\n✅ **Enqueue**: Inserts an element at the rear of the queue. Before enqueueing, it’s crucial to check if the queue is full (overflow condition). If the queue is empty, `front` and `rear` are set to 0.\n\n✅ **Dequeue**: Removes an element from the front of the queue. Before dequeuing, it’s important to check if the queue is empty (underflow condition). After deleting the last element, both pointers are reset to -1.\n\n✅ **Peek**: Retrieves the front element without removing it.\n\n### C Implementation Snippet:\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n#define SIZE 5\nint queue[SIZE], front = -1, rear = -1;\n\nvoid enqueue(int data) {\n    if(rear == SIZE - 1) printf("Overflow\\n");\n    else {\n        if(front == -1) front = 0;\n        queue[++rear] = data;\n    }\n}\n\nvoid dequeue() {\n    if(front == -1) printf("Underflow\\n");\n    else {\n        printf("Dequeued: %d\\n", queue[front]);\n        if(front == rear) front = rear = -1;\n        else front++;\n    }\n}\n\nvoid peek() {\n    if(front != -1) printf("Front: %d\\n", queue[front]);\n}\n```\n\nIn this implementation, **overflow** occurs when `rear` reaches `SIZE-1` and no more insertions can be made. **Underflow** occurs when `front` is -1, meaning no elements exist to dequeue.\n\nUnderstanding these operations and their conditions ensures that queues are implemented correctly and efficiently in C, and they form the basis of many real-world applications like CPU scheduling, resource sharing, and more.',
