                          answer:
                            'A **priority queue** is an advanced form of a queue where each element has an associated priority. In a priority queue, elements with higher priority are removed before elements with lower priority, regardless of their insertion order. If two elements have the same priority, they are dequeued according to their order of arrival.\n\nPriority queues can be implemented using arrays, linked lists, or heaps (for efficient implementations). In the uploaded document, the priority queue is implemented using an array and **heapify** principles to ensure that the highest priority element remains at the top.\n\n### Basic Operations:\n✅ **Insertion (enqueue)**: When a new element is inserted, it’s placed based on its priority. If the queue is empty, `front` and `rear` are set to 0 and the element is inserted. Otherwise, the element is inserted in the appropriate position to maintain the order of priority.\n\n✅ **Deletion (dequeue)**: The element with the highest priority is removed first. In the array implementation, this means removing the front element (since the highest priority is kept at the front). The subsequent elements are shifted to fill the gap.\n\n### Example C Implementation Snippet:\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n#define MAX 5\nint pri_que[MAX], front = -1, rear = -1;\n\nvoid insert_by_priority(int data) {\n    if(rear >= MAX - 1) {\n        printf("Overflow\\n");\n        return;\n    }\n    if((front == -1) && (rear == -1)) {\n        front++; rear++;\n        pri_que[rear] = data;\n        return;\n    }\n    int i;\n    for(i = 0; i <= rear; i++) {\n        if(data >= pri_que[i]) {\n            for(int j = rear + 1; j > i; j--)\n                pri_que[j] = pri_que[j - 1];\n            pri_que[i] = data;\n            rear++;\n            return;\n        }\n    }\n    pri_que[++rear] = data;\n}\n```\n\n### Applications:\n✅ **CPU Scheduling**: High-priority processes are scheduled first.\n✅ **Dijkstra\'s Algorithm**: Finding the shortest path in graphs.\n✅ **Resource Management**: Managing tasks based on priority levels.\n\nThis concept ensures that critical tasks are processed earlier, making it invaluable in real-time and multitasking environments.',
