                          answer:
                            'A **circular queue** is a linear data structure that follows the **First In, First Out (FIFO)** principle but solves the space wastage problem that occurs in linear queues. In a linear queue, when elements are dequeued from the front, the empty spaces in the array cannot be reused even if there is space at the beginning. This leads to inefficient memory usage.\n\nCircular queues address this by making the queue\'s end connect to the front, forming a circle. The `front` and `rear` pointers are updated using modulo arithmetic to wrap around the queue\'s array when they reach the end, thereby using the freed space efficiently.\n\n### Implementation Details:\n✅ **Front and Rear Pointers**:  \n- Initially, both are set to -1 to denote an empty queue.  \n- When the first element is enqueued, both pointers are set to 0.  \n- **Enqueue**: Rear is incremented by `(rear + 1) % size`.  \n- **Dequeue**: Front is incremented by `(front + 1) % size`.\n\n✅ **Circular Increment**:  \nThe modulo operation ensures that when `rear` or `front` reaches the end of the array (size - 1), the next increment brings it back to 0, making the queue circular.\n\n### Overflow and Underflow:\n✅ **Overflow**: Occurs when `(rear + 1) % size == front`, meaning the queue is full.\n✅ **Underflow**: Occurs when `front` is -1.\n\n### Example C Implementation:\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n#define SIZE 5\nint queue[SIZE], front = -1, rear = -1;\n\nvoid enqueue(int data) {\n    if ((rear + 1) % SIZE == front) printf("Queue is full\\n");\n    else {\n        if (front == -1) front = rear = 0;\n        else rear = (rear + 1) % SIZE;\n        queue[rear] = data;\n    }\n}\n\nvoid dequeue() {\n    if (front == -1) printf("Queue is empty\\n");\n    else {\n        printf("Dequeued: %d\\n", queue[front]);\n        if (front == rear) front = rear = -1;\n        else front = (front + 1) % SIZE;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nCircular queues are particularly useful in applications like CPU scheduling, streaming data buffers, and resource sharing. By leveraging the circular nature and modulo arithmetic, they provide an efficient solution to the memory wastage problem seen in linear queues.',
